The mesial view of a maxillary first premolar is {{c1::trapezoidal}} in shape.
In a maxillary first premolar the lingual M-D is {{c1::narrower::wider or narrower}} than the buccal M-D.
The lingual cusp of the {{c1::maxillary first premolar:: maxillary first premolar or maxillary second premolar}} is shorter than the facial and is the shortest of maxillary pemolar cusps
The lingual cusp of the maxillary first premolar is offset to the {{c1::mesial::mesial or distal.}}
The lingual HOC of the maxillary first premolar is at the {{c1::middle third::incisal third, middle third, or cervivcal third.}}
The facial and lingual cusps are centered over the root truck in a {{c1::maxiallary first premolar.:: what tooth}}
A strong {{c1::mesial::mesial or distal}} marginal groove is visible in maxilary first premolar.
There is a {{c1::mesial::mesial or distal}} concavity from the root trunk to the cervical portion of the crown in a {{c2::maxillary first premolar::tooth}}.
The mesial contact area of maxillary first premolar is {{c1::facial::facial or lingual}} to the facial-lingual midline.
The distal view has a {{c1::shorter::shorter or longer}} Occlusal-Cervical dimention than the mesial view of a maxillary first premolar.
More of the occlusal surface is visible from a {{c1::distal::distal or mesial}} view of maxillary first premolar.
There is no distinct {{c1::distal::mesial or distal}} concavity on a maxillary first premolar.
The distal contact area is slightly {{c1::more cervical and facial::position}} than the mesial contact area of maxillary first premolar.
The occlusal outline of a maxillary first premolar is {{c1::hexagonal.}}
The maxillary first premolar is wider {{c1::F-L::M-D or F-L}} than {{c1::M-D::M-D or F-L}}.
The occlusal outline of the maxillary first premolar tapers towards {{c1::lingual::buccal or lingual}}.
The lingual cusp of a maxillary first premolar is offset {{c1::mesially::mesialy or distally.}}
The {{c1::mesial}} marginal ridge is shorter than the {{c1::distal}} marginal ridge of a maxillary first premolar.
The mesial outline of the maxillary first premolar is indented with the mesial marginal {{c1::groove}}.
The mesial and distal pits of a maxillary first premolar are {{c2::well seperated::orientation to eachother}} by the {{c1::central groove. }}
There are {{c1::less::more or less}} secondary grooves is a maxillary first premolar compared to a second premolar.

The mesial and distal contact areas are both positioned more facially, but the mesial contact area is more {{c1::lingual::facial or lingaul}} than the distal contact area of a maxillary first premolar.
From an occlusal view of the maxillary first premolar the DB cusp ridge and distal marginal ridge form an/a {{c1::acute::right or acute}} angle.
From an occlusal view of the maillary first premolar the MB ridge and mesial marginal ridge form an/a {{c1::right::acute, right, or obtuse}} angle.
The maxillary first premolar has {{c1::three::how many}} different root types.
A single root with distinct mesial concavity, two root canals, and a kidney bean shaped cervical cross section is a type {{c1::1}} root.
A bifurcated root with a short root trunk, two roots of almost equal length is a type {{c1::2}} root.
Type {{c1::2}} roots are the most common root form for a maxillary first premolar.
A {{c1::laminated}} root resembles a type two root with bifuration but it has a longer root trunk. This is known as type {{c1::3}}.
{{c2::Trifurcation}} is possible in a maxillary first premolar: {{c1::2}} buccal roots and {{c1::1}} lingual root. Pulp crowns can be seperate or connected.
